GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 1
SENATE BILL 1044
Short Title: Foundational Mathematics Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Corbin, Hise, and Lee (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
May 4, 2026
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO IMPROVE GRADE LEVEL PROFICIENCY IN MATHEMATICS, CODIFY
3 THE OFFICE OF LEARNING RESEARCH (OLR) AT THE NORTH CAROLINA
4 COLLABORATORY, REQUIRE OLR TO EVALUATE VENDORS OF
5 INSTRUCTIONAL MATERIALS, TO ESTABLISH THE AI INSTRUCTIONAL
6 SUPPORT PROGRAM, AND TO APPROPRIATE FUNDS FOR THOSE PURPOSES.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8
9 PART I. HIGH QUALITY MATHEMATICS INSTRUCTION
10 SECTION 1.(a) Article 8 of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is amended by
11 adding a new Part to read:
12 "Part 1C. High-Quality Mathematics Instruction.
13 "§ 115C-83.20. State goal.
14 The goal of the State is to ensure that every student has mathematics skills at or above grade
15 level by the end of each grade and continues to progress so that he or she can have the
16 mathematics skills needed for secondary education and career success. The State Board of
17 Education and the Department of Public Instruction shall provide technical assistance as needed
18 to aid local school administrative units in reaching this goal and implementing all provisions of
19 this Part.
20 "§ 115C-83.21. Purposes.
21 The purposes of this Part are to ensure that (i) difficulty with mathematics skill development
22 is identified before students transition to a new grade, (ii) students receive appropriate
23 mathematics interventions to address difficulty with mathematics skill development and to
24 remediate math skill deficiencies, and (iii) each student and his or her parent or guardian be
25 informed of the student's academic needs and progress.
26 "§ 115C-83.22. Definitions.
27 The following definitions apply in this Part:
28 (1) Difficulty with mathematics skill development. – Performing at or below
29 grade level on screening assessments administered pursuant to
30 G.S. 115C-83.24.
31 (2) High-quality instruction. – Instruction that meets the criteria set forth in
32 G.S. 115C-83.23.
33 (3) Major mathematics skills. – Mathematics skills identified by the State Board
34 of Education to show grade level proficiency.
*S1044-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Progressing toward grade level standards. – Showing improved performance
2 in major mathematics skills based on results on the screening assessment
3 administered pursuant to G.S. 115C-83.24.
4 "§ 115C-83.23. High-quality instruction.
5 Governing bodies of public school units shall implement high-quality mathematics
6 instruction for students in kindergarten through grade eight that meets the following criteria:
7 (1) Aligns with the North Carolina Standard Course of Study.
8 (2) Is evidence-based.
9 (3) Engages students and provides them with relevant challenges and pathways
10 to deeper understanding.
11 (4) Provides students at all levels of language proficiency with opportunities to
12 use written and oral forms of communication to learn and demonstrate
13 understanding of mathematics skills.
14 (5) Is for at least 60 minutes per day.
15 "§ 115C-83.24. Mathematics screening assessment.
16 (a) All students in kindergarten through grade eight shall be assessed at least three times
17 per school year with formative and diagnostic mathematics assessments made available to local
18 school administrative units by the State Board of Education pursuant to G.S. 115C-174.11(a1).
19 The first assessment in a given school year shall be administered within 30 days of the start of
20 the school year. Assessments shall meet the following criteria:
21 (1) Be valid and reliable.
22 (2) Align with the North Carolina Standard Course of Study.
23 (3) Align with this Part.
24 (4) Yield data that can be used with the Education Value-Added Assessment
25 System (EVAAS) to analyze student data to identify root causes for difficulty
26 with mathematics skill development and to determine actions to address them.
27 (b) The Department of Public Instruction shall partner with the vendor selected pursuant
28 to subsection (c) of this section to provide guidance and professional development to teachers
29 and administrators on the following to ensure that mathematics screening assessment data is used
30 to meaningfully inform instruction:
31 (1) Using mathematics screening assessment results to influence in-class
32 instruction.
33 (2) Planning for student interventions and MSPs.
34 (3) Progress monitoring of students based on mathematics screening assessment
35 results.
36 (c) The Department of Public Instruction shall develop and issue a request for proposals
37 (RFP) for a mathematics screening assessment tool to be administered to all students in
38 kindergarten through grade eight consistent with the requirements of Part 1C of Article 8 of
39 Chapter 115C. The Department may issue a new RFP if the State Board or Department
40 determines that a new contract is needed to comply with the provisions of subsection (a1) of this
41 section or G.S. 115C-83.24. The RFP shall require that proposals include at least the following:
42 (1) Assessments that align with the standard course of study.
43 (2) Assessments that can be administered three times per year, with progressing
44 standards for each subsequent assessment.
45 (3) Progress monitoring tools for teachers and administrators to be able to track
46 student progress.
47 (4) Provide results of assessments to teachers and parents no later than 15
48 calendar days after the assessment is administered.
49 (5) Ability to identify students in need of intervention.
50 (6) Ability to report results of assessments to the Department.
51 "§ 115C-83.25. Interventions and Mathematics Success Plans (MSPs).
Page 2 Senate Bill 1044-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) Students who are not grade level proficient in mathematics skills based on the results
2 of either (i) the first diagnostic or formative assessment of a school year or (ii) the first diagnostic
3 or formative assessment of the second semester of a school year administered pursuant to
4 G.S. 115C-83.24(a), shall be provided with intervention and remediation services documented in
5 a Mathematics Success Plan (MSP) that meets the requirements of this section and aligns with
6 the guidance and professional development provided pursuant to G.S. 115C-83.24(b). Students
7 shall continue to receive an MSP through the end of eighth grade or when the student
8 demonstrates grade level proficiency on the third mathematics screening assessment in a given
9 school year, whichever is earlier.
10 (b) A student's parent or guardian shall be given notice that the student has been identified
11 as having difficulty with mathematics skill development and that an MSP is being developed.
12 (c) The MSP shall be developed by a team consisting of the following:
13 (1) The math teacher of the student.
14 (2) Other relevant school personnel.
15 (d) The MSP shall be regularly adjusted based on multiple data sources indicating that
16 the student is not progressing toward grade level standards in one or more major mathematics
17 skills. Based on the most recently collected data, an MSP shall include the following information,
18 specific to the identified student:
19 (1) The specific mathematics skill deficiencies identified by the assessment data.
20 (2) Goals and benchmarks for growth.
21 (3) The means by which progress will be monitored and evaluated.
22 (4) The specific additional mathematics interventions the student will receive.
23 (5) Any additional services the teacher deems appropriate to accelerate the
24 student's mathematics skill development.
25 (e) A multitiered system of support intervention may be used to satisfy the requirements
26 of this section if all of the components of subsection (d) of this section are incorporated in the
27 intervention.
28 (f) The Department shall develop the following model documentation of compliance
29 with the requirements of this section:
30 (1) An MSP checklist.
31 (2) An alternative document for use with a multitiered system of support
32 intervention."
33 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 115C-174.11 reads as rewritten:
34 "§ 115C-174.11. Components of the testing program.
35 (a) Reading Assessment Instruments for Kindergarten, First, Second, and Third Grades.
36 – The State Board of Education shall develop, adopt, and provide to the local school
37 administrative units developmentally appropriate individualized assessment instruments aligned
38 with the standard course of study and Part 1A of Article 8 of this Chapter for the kindergarten,
39 first, second, and third grades. Local school administrative units shall use these assessment
40 instruments provided to them by the State Board for kindergarten, first, second, and third grade
41 students to assess progress, diagnose difficulties, and inform instruction and remediation needs.
42 Local school administrative units shall not use standardized tests for summative assessment of
43 kindergarten, first, and second grade students except as required as a condition of receiving
44 federal grants.
45 (a1) Mathematics Assessment Instrument for kindergarten through eighth grade. – The
46 State Board of Education shall adopt and provide to the local school administrative units a series
47 of mathematics screener assessment instruments aligned with the standard course of study and
48 Part 1C of Article 8 of this Chapter for students in kindergarten through eighth grade. Public
49 school units shall administer the assessment instrument made available to them by the State
50 Board to assess progress, diagnose difficulties, and inform instruction and remediation needs for
51 students in kindergarten through eighth grade. Public school units shall not use these formative
Senate Bill 1044-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 and diagnostic assessments for summative assessment of students in kindergarten through eight
2 grade, except as required as a condition of receiving federal grants.
3 (b) Repealed by Session Laws 2009-451, s. 7.20(c), effective July 1, 2009.
4 (c) Annual Testing Program. –
5 (1) The State Board of Education shall adopt the tests for grades three through 12
6 that are required by federal law or as a condition of a federal grant. These tests
7 shall be designed to measure progress toward reading, communication skills,
8 and mathematics for grades three through eight, and toward competencies for
9 grades nine through 12. Students who do not pass the tests adopted for eighth
10 grade shall be provided remedial instruction in the ninth grade.
11 (2) If the State Board of Education finds that additional testing in grades three
12 through 12 is desirable to allow comparisons with national indicators of
13 student achievement, that testing shall be conducted with the smallest size
14 sample of students necessary to assure valid comparisons with other states.
15 (3) Repealed by Session Laws 2014-78, s. 3(a), effective July 1, 2014.
16 (4) To the extent funds are made available, the State Board of Education shall use
17 a competitive bid process to adopt one nationally norm-referenced college
18 admissions test to make available to local school administrative units, regional
19 schools, and charter schools to administer to all students in the eleventh grade
20 unless the student has already taken a comparable test and scored at or above
21 a level set by the State Board. The State Board of Education shall require the
22 administration of an alternate to the nationally norm-referenced college
23 admissions test or an alternate precursor test to the nationally norm-referenced
24 college admissions test to a student who (i) exhibits severe and pervasive
25 delays in all areas of conceptual, linguistic, and academic development and in
26 adaptive behaviors, including communication, daily living skills, and
27 self-care, (ii) is following the extended content standards of the Standard
28 Course of Study as provided in G.S. 115C-81.5, or is following a course of
29 study that, upon completing high school, may not lead to admission into a
30 college-level course of study resulting in a college degree, and (iii) has a
31 written parental request for an alternate assessment.
32 The State Board of Education shall ensure that parents of students enrolled
33 in all public schools, including charter and regional schools, have the
34 necessary information to make informed decisions regarding participation in
35 the nationally norm-referenced college admissions test and precursor test.
36 Alternate assessment and nationally norm-referenced college admissions
37 test assessment results of students with disabilities shall be included in school
38 accountability reports, including charter and regional schools, provided by the
39 State Board of Education.
40 (d) Except as provided in subsection (c) of this section, the State Board of Education shall
41 not require the public schools to administer any standardized tests except for those required by
42 federal law or as a condition of a federal grant.
43 The State Board of Education shall adopt and provide to local school administrative units all
44 tests required by federal law or as a condition of a federal grant."
