21 SECTION 1.(h) The Department shall select a vendor based on a proposal submitted
22 pursuant to G.S. 115C-83.24(c), as enacted by this act, by January 15, 2028, and the State Board
23 of Education shall make assessments available to public school units for use beginning with the
24 2028-2029 school year.
25 SECTION 1.(i) Beginning with the 2028-2029 school year, public school units shall
26 only use materials approved by the Office of Learning Research pursuant to Part 3 of this act for
27 mathematics instruction. MSPs developed pursuant to G.S. 115C-83.25 shall include a list of
28 high-quality instructional materials approved by OLR pursuant to Part 3 of this act to be used for
29 implementation of the MSP.
30 SECTION 1.(j) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
31 Public Instruction the sum of twenty-one million dollars ($21,000,000) in recurring funds
32 beginning with the 2026-2027 fiscal year to implement the provisions of this section.
33 SECTION 1.(k) Subsection (a) of this section becomes effective July 1, 2027.
34 Subsection (j) of this section expires June 30, 2031.
35
36 PART II. INITIAL REVIEW OF HIGH-QUALITY INSTRUCTIONAL MATERIALS
37 SECTION 2.(a) The Office of Learning Research (OLR), in consultation with the
38 Department of Public Instruction, researchers in the field of mathematics instruction, and other
39 relevant stakeholders, shall establish a process for evaluating vendors of instructional materials
40 intended for use in kindergarten through grade eight math instruction based on the following
41 criteria:
42 (1) Alignment with the standard course of study.
43 (2) Use of sound mathematical and evidence-based pedagogical strategies.
44 (3) Implementation of mathematical learning trajectories that are coherent and
45 mathematically accurate.
46 (4) Evidence of positive effects in other states.
47 (5) Inclusion of intervention materials that support the development of
48 grade-level math knowledge.
49 (6) Extent to vendor-led professional development accompanying materials
50 enhances teacher knowledge of evidence-based approaches to teaching math.
Senate Bill 1044-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 2.(b) OLR shall provide a list of vendors approved pursuant to subsection
2 (a) of this section to the Department of Public Instruction by April 30, 2027. The Department
3 shall distribute this list to public school units by June 1, 2027.
4
5 PART III. LONG-TERM REVIEW OF HIGH-QUALITY INSTRUCTIONAL
6 MATERIALS
7 SECTION 3.(a) The North Carolina Collaboratory (Collaboratory) shall study
8 models used in other states to develop high-quality instructional materials at the state level and
9 report on the results of that study to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee by
10 April 15, 2027. The report shall include recommendations for how to implement a model to
11 develop high-quality instructional materials in North Carolina, including at least the following:
12 (1) Feasibility.
13 (2) Infrastructure and personnel needs.
14 (3) Analysis of start-up costs.
15 (4) Analysis of longer-term funding needs.
16 SECTION 3.(b) The Collaboratory shall conduct analyses of instructional quality,
17 teacher practice, and student outcomes based on the provisions of this act. The Collaboratory
18 shall use continuous improvement tools, including readiness assessments, observational rubrics,
19 high-quality instructional material implementation checklists, and educator surveys when
20 conducting these analyses. The Collaboratory shall report on the results of these analyses by
21 December 15, 2031.
22 SECTION 3.(c) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Board of
23 Governors of the University of North Carolina the sum of two million five hundred thousand
24 dollars ($2,500,000) in nonrecurring funds for the 2026-2027 fiscal year to allocate to the
25 Collaboratory to implement the provisions of Parts II and III of this act.
26
27 PART IV. EFFECTIVE DATE
28 SECTION 4. Except as otherwise provided, this act becomes effective July 1, 2026.
